1
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:09,233
Imagine a popular online service inundated with requests. Without control, it quickly crashes, denying access to

2
00:00:09,333 --> 00:00:15,566
everyone. Rate limiters act as essential gatekeepers, controlling the flow of traffic to protect your systems. They

3
00:00:15,666 --> 00:00:21,899
prevent malicious attacks like Denial of Service, stop resource abuse, and ensure fair usage for all clients.

4
00:00:23,500 --> 00:00:27,399
At its core, a rate limiter is a mechanism to control the rate at which an entity can send requests or consume

5
00:00:27,500 --> 00:00:31,399
resources. It sits between clients and your services, evaluating each incoming request against predefined limits. If a

6
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:35,399
request exceeds the allowed rate, the limiter will either block, delay, or reject it, preventing your backend from being

7
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:39,399
overwhelmed.

8
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:47,149
The Fixed Window Counter is one of the simplest algorithms. It divides time into discrete, non-overlapping windows,

9
00:00:47,250 --> 00:00:53,399
like one-minute intervals. Each request within a window increments a counter, and once the limit is reached, further

10
00:00:53,500 --> 00:00:59,649
requests are blocked until the next window starts. However, this method can suffer from a 'burst' problem, allowing

11
00:00:59,750 --> 00:01:05,900
double the allowed rate if requests arrive heavily at the end of one window and the start of the next.

12
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:14,400
To address the fixed window's burst issue, the Sliding Window Log algorithm maintains a sorted list of timestamps for

13
00:01:14,500 --> 00:01:21,400
every request from a client. When a new request arrives, it counts all timestamps within the last 'N' seconds,

14
00:01:21,500 --> 00:01:28,400
dynamically trimming older entries. This provides highly accurate rate limiting, but its memory consumption can be

15
00:01:28,500 --> 00:01:35,400
significant, especially under high traffic, as it stores every request's timestamp.

16
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:43,150
The Token Bucket algorithm models a bucket that fills with tokens at a constant rate, up to a maximum capacity. Each

17
00:01:43,250 --> 00:01:49,400
incoming request tries to consume a token. If a token is available, the request proceeds. If not, it's rejected. This

18
00:01:49,500 --> 00:01:55,650
approach gracefully handles bursts, allowing requests to consume accumulated tokens, but still enforces an average rate

19
00:01:55,750 --> 00:02:01,900
limit determined by the token fill rate.

20
00:02:03,500 --> 00:02:09,650
In contrast to the Token Bucket, the Leaky Bucket algorithm emphasizes a steady output rate. Requests are added to a

21
00:02:09,750 --> 00:02:15,900
'bucket,' and they 'leak' out at a constant, predefined processing rate. If the bucket is full, new incoming requests

22
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:22,150
are discarded. This mechanism is ideal for smoothing out bursty traffic, ensuring that the downstream service receives

23
00:02:22,250 --> 00:02:28,400
requests at a very consistent pace.

24
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,400
In modern distributed systems, rate limiters can't just live on a single server. Achieving global rate limits requires

25
00:02:35,500 --> 00:02:40,900
coordination across multiple instances, often using a shared, highly available data store like Redis. Common deployment

26
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:46,400
points include API Gateways, which act as the first line of defense, or within service meshes. This ensures consistent

27
00:02:46,500 --> 00:02:51,900
enforcement, regardless of which service instance receives the request.

28
00:02:53,500 --> 00:02:58,150
We've explored the critical role of rate limiters, from protecting against overload to ensuring fair resource use. We

29
00:02:58,250 --> 00:03:02,900
examined algorithms like Fixed Window, Sliding Window Log, Token Bucket, and Leaky Bucket, each with its own trade-offs.

30
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:07,650
Remember, choosing the right algorithm depends on your specific needs, and in distributed environments, careful

31
00:03:07,750 --> 00:03:12,400
coordination is key. Rate limiting is a powerful tool for robust system design.
